          "text": "Base directory for this skill: /home/leon0399/.claude/skills/iterative-review-refinement\n\n# Iterative Review Refinement\n\n## Overview\n\n**One reviewer is anecdote. Two parallel reviewers with independent defaults are signal. Convergence — not round count — is the stop condition.**\n\nDocuments that look right on first pass routinely contain factual errors, stale cross-references, and subtle logic gaps that a single careful read won't catch. The fix is not \"read more carefully\" — it's pressure-testing via independent reviewers, verifying each load-bearing finding against primary sources, and iterating until both reviewers stop finding substantive issues.\n\nThis is TDD for documents. The draft is production code. Reviewers are tests. Convergence is green.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- Finished initial draft of a design memo, research report, plan, RFC, analysis, or technical spec\n- Document will inform load-bearing decisions or land in a PR\n- Errors are costly to find later (after merge, after implementation starts, after stakeholders rely on it)\n- You're tempted to ship after one read-through because \"it looks right\"\n\n**Don't use for:**\n- Scratch notes, single-paragraph comments, ephemeral text\n- Documents already gated by mandatory human review with equivalent rigor\n- Trivial fixes where review overhead exceeds value\n- Code: use code-review skills instead (this is for prose deliverables)\n\n## Specialist subagents\n\nTwo user-level specialists are available and SHOULD be preferred over `general-purpose`:\n\n- **`iterative-review-reviewer`** (cyan) — primary GP-side reviewer for the loop. Inherits this skill's methodology, audit-surface checklist, output format, anti-rationalization rule, and primary-source verification mandates. Per-round prompt shrinks to the round delta.\n- **`adversarial-reviewer-fallback`** (red) — hostile substitute when `plugin:codex:adversarial-review` is unavailable (usage limit, tool failure). Defaults to literal readings, parallel-callout focus, and Codex-class blind-spot coverage.\n\nWhen dispatching parallel reviewers, the canonical pair is **`plugin:codex:adversarial-review` + `iterative-review-reviewer`**. Fallback pair when Codex is down: **`iterative-review-reviewer` + `adversarial-reviewer-fallback`**. Don't pair two `general-purpose` agents — they share blind spots.\n\n### Dispatch examples\n\nCanonical pair — Codex + GP-side specialist (default when Codex is available). Dispatch BOTH in a single message with parallel tool calls:\n\n```typescript\nBash({\n  command: `node \"$CODEX_COMPANION_PATH\" adversarial-review \"--background \\\"<prompt — see 'Codex prompting tactics' subsection below for required framing>\\\"\"`,\n  description: \"Codex round N\",\n  run_in_background: true\n})\nAgent({\n  subagent_type: \"iterative-review-reviewer\",\n  description: \"Round N verification\",\n  prompt: \"Doc: <abs-path>. Round N. v<N-1>→v<N> delta: <fixes applied this round>. Prior-round findings: <link or 'see revision-history lines X-Y'>. Optional focus: <surfaces to probe>.\"\n})\n```\n\nFallback pair — when Codex is unavailable (usage limit, transient failure). Dispatch both specialists in parallel:\n\n```typescript\nAgent({\n  subagent_type: \"iterative-review-reviewer\",\n  description: \"Round N verification\",\n  prompt: \"Doc: <abs-path>. Round N. v<N-1>→v<N> delta: <fixes applied this round>.\"\n})\nAgent({\n  subagent_type: \"adversarial-reviewer-fallback\",\n  description: \"Round N hostile probe\",\n  prompt: \"Doc: <abs-path>. Round N. Primary reviewer dispatched in parallel. Hostile-probe focus: <sites the primary might rationalize / surfaces Codex would catch>.\"\n})\n```\n\nThe fallback pair is weaker than Codex + specialist because both agents share Claude's blind spots — but stronger than a single reviewer because the hostile-framing default produces orthogonal findings on the same model.\n\nPer-round prompt shrinks from ~1,500 words (when methodology lives in the prompt) to ~150-300 words (when methodology lives in the agents' system prompts). If you find yourself re-pasting the audit-surface checklist or output format into per-round prompts, the agent system prompts need tightening — the methodology should ride on the agent, not the prompt.\n\n## Core Loop\n\n```\n1. Draft vN exists, ready for adversarial review\n       │\n       ▼\n2. Dispatch ≥2 INDEPENDENT reviewers in PARALLEL\n   - Codex via plugin:codex:adversarial-review (primary)\n   - iterative-review-reviewer specialist (GP-side)\n   - adversarial-reviewer-fallback if Codex unavailable\n       │\n       ▼\n3. Synthesize findings: dedupe across reviewers, classify P0 / P1 / P2\n       │\n       ▼\n4. INDEPENDENTLY VERIFY each load-bearing finding against primary sources\n   (do NOT trust the reviewer's assertion — check it yourself)\n       │\n       ▼\n5. Apply verified fixes → bump version (vN → vN+1) → write revision-history entry\n       │\n       ▼\n6. Converged?  ── no ──▶ back to step 2\n                  │\n                 yes\n                  ▼\n               ship\n```\n\n## Briefing the Reviewers\n\nReviewers default to thin context. Parallel reviewers regress to single-reviewer signal if both are briefed poorly. Brief each one explicitly:\n\n- **Paste prior-round findings verbatim** so the new round doesn't re-flag already-fixed issues\n- **Name files with full absolute or repo-relative paths** — don't make reviewers grep\n- **For gitignored targets, drop `--base` flags** (some review tools bail on gitignored content otherwise)\n- **Tell general-purpose agents to use the project runtime** (e.g. `uv run python3`, `bun run`) for arithmetic and code checks — not the global interpreter\n- **State the document's purpose and load-bearing claims**: what decisions does it gate, what's already been verified, what's known to be uncertain\n- **List the supporting artifacts** (e.g. `sources.jsonl`, `bibliography.bib`, companion notebooks) and ask reviewers to check consistency across them\n\nA thin brief produces thin findings.\n\n### Exploit reviewer blind spots\n\nCodex and general-purpose agents have systematically different failure modes — observed across 40+ rounds of split-decision findings:\n\n- **General-purpose agents are strong at:** arithmetic audits, dataclass-field consistency, primary-source verification when given the right tool flags, exhaustive grep-driven sweeps.\n- **General-purpose agents miss:** parallel-spec-contract drift (the same fix not propagated to all sites), diagnostic-vs-production parity, contradictions they rationalize away (\"this prose is describing X-from-another-angle so it doesn't contradict the new fix\").\n- **Codex is strong at:** parallel-callout detection, contract-drift across module boundaries, hostile probes of the rewrite that just landed, catching reviewer rationalizations.\n- **Codex misses:** subtle arithmetic when its tool-call flags fetch incomplete data (`gh issue view --json body` misses comments; `git diff` misses gitignored files; targeted grep can miss content past read-window).\n\nDispatch both, every round. A single-reviewer \"converged\" verdict is unreliable: ~⅓ of rounds in long iterations have split decisions where one reviewer's miss would have shipped a load-bearing bug.\n\n### Reviewer-tool gotchas to flag in the brief\n\n- **GitHub issue cites:** if a memo references a GitHub issue's body, brief reviewers to use `gh issue view N --comments` (NOT `--json body`). A common bug pattern is \"claim X is per issue N's recent comment\"; if a reviewer fetches only the body, they will report the cite as factually wrong when it's actually accurate.\n- **`git diff` on gitignored targets:** force reviewers to read the target file directly via `cat`/`nl -ba`/`Read`. Some review tools default to `git diff <base>...HEAD` and silently skip gitignored content, returning a \"no diff to review\" false-positive.\n- **Truncated tool output:** large files read via `sed -n 'A,Bp'` may miss content past line B. For document-wide invariant audits, instruct reviewers to grep the full file rather than spot-read ranges.\n\n### Reviewer steering tactics\n\nBeyond initial briefing, the following moves reliably surface findings reviewers otherwise miss:\n\n1. **Adversarial framing.** When dispatching the second reviewer, frame their job as finding what the FIRST reviewer would miss. Phrase: \"Be HOSTILE. What would [Codex / the other reviewer] catch that this one didn't?\" Subagents given this framing surface parallel-callout and contract-drift items they otherwise rationalize away.\n2. **Recalibration warnings.** When a reviewer cleared a contradiction in a previous round and the next round found it via the other reviewer, brief the previously-wrong reviewer explicitly: \"You rationalized X as Y last round; don't do it again. Treat literal readings as load-bearing.\" Produces corrected behavior on the next pass.\n3. **Forbidden-phrase grep gates.** After a normative fix, specify a `rg \"stale-phrase-1|stale-phrase-2\"` invocation that should return zero active-body hits. This mechanizes verification — reviewers can't hand-wave that \"the prose corrects it elsewhere\"; if the grep tripped, the fix is incomplete. Caveat: a corrective negation (e.g. \"not a global knob\") will trip a gate that includes \"global knob\" as a forbidden bigram — flag this explicitly so the reviewer knows to inspect the match, not reflexively report it.\n4. **Two-phase audits.** When verifying a fix that's supposed to be additive-only (new section, no spec-body change), split the review into Phase A (guard verification — spot-check unchanged sites) and Phase B (content correctness — verify the new claims). Either phase alone misses bugs: A misses content errors, B misses unintended spec drift.\n5. **Primary-source-verification commands, not just verification mandates.** \"Verify against issue N\" gets a thin probe; \"run `gh issue view N --comments` and confirm the cited claim appears in the comment body\" gets the right probe. Always specify the exact tool invocation, including flags.\n\n### Codex prompting tactics (beyond the plugin description)\n\nThe `plugin:codex:adversarial-review` and `plugin:codex:review` skills document foreground-vs-background selection, argument preservation, and verbatim output return. These additional operational details are NOT in the plugin description but matter in practice:\n\n1. **Gitignored targets need explicit framing.** Codex defaults to `git diff <base>...HEAD` and bails silently on gitignored content (returning \"nothing to review\" false-positives). Prefix the prompt with `GITIGNORED-TARGET-REVIEW. READ DIRECTLY via nl -ba <path> or cat <path>.` Drop `--base` from the invocation.\n2. **Sanitize prompts to ASCII.** Special characters break the companion script's zsh quoting: `≤`, smart quotes, em-dashes, and unescaped backticks. Use `<=`, plain quotes, hyphens, and escape backticks or describe them in prose. A failed dispatch with exit 1 and `(eval):1: unmatched` in the output is the signature.\n3. **Codex may emit JSON intermediate verdicts mid-investigation.** The first `Assistant message captured` line in the output file may be an intermediate \"approve\" while Codex is still in tool-call phase. Read the LAST captured assistant message for the final verdict, AND look for the `# Codex Adversarial Review` header block at the end. If the file ends mid-tool-call, Codex truncated before final emit — re-dispatch with the same prompt.\n4. **`gh issue view --json body` skips comments.** When briefing Codex to verify a `#N` cross-reference, specify `gh issue view N --comments`. Otherwise Codex will fetch only the issue body and report a \"factually wrong cite\" finding when the claim actually appears in a comment.\n5. **Usage-limit fallback.** Codex returns \"You've hit your usage limit. Try again at HH:MM\" mid-loop without warning. When this happens, either wait for the reset OR spawn a second general-purpose subagent with the hostile-find-what-Codex-would-find framing (see \"Reviewer steering tactics\" above). Don't ship on a single reviewer.\n6. **Codex sandbox is read-only.** Codex can't write files, even if the prompt asks. Useful for adversarial verification (the reviewer can't accidentally apply a fix), but flag if the brief contains write actions — Codex will report inability to act rather than a content finding.\n\n## Verify Before Fix\n\nA reviewer pointing at a \"bug\" can be:\n- **Right** → apply the fix\n- **Wrong about the primary source** → cite back, don't apply, document the disagreement\n- **Right about the symptom but wrong about the cause** → apply a different fix targeted at the actual cause\n\n**Always verify load-bearing findings against primary sources before changing the document.** Especially:\n- Version numbers, arXiv IDs, DOI strings, paper titles, author lists\n- File paths, function names, API signatures, deprecation status\n- Units, sign conventions, coordinate frames, axis orientations\n- Numeric values, equation coefficients, table entries\n\nUse WebFetch on the abstract page. Grep the repo. Run the snippet under the project runtime. Don't apply a fix because a reviewer asserted it confidently — reviewers (including AI agents) hallucinate.\n\n## Audit surfaces — where bugs hide\n\nA normative spec fix in long-form prose often fails to propagate to parallel surfaces. Every spec-block fix needs a global grep + sweep of ALL these surfaces, not just the named fix site. The list grows monotonically as a loop proceeds — track new surface classes when they appear:\n\n1. **Equation prose** (math definitions in scientific notation)\n2. **Standalone math blocks** (rendered LaTeX-style formulas — frequently lag the prose paragraph above them)\n3. **Algorithm-step pseudocode** (imperative implementation steps that USE the equations)\n4. **Diagnostic / sanity-check code blocks** (helper functions; must match production selection-and-reduction logic exactly)\n5. **Worked-example narrative** (illustrative tables; \"the contribution is from the closest arm\" can survive after the equation prose was corrected to \"argmax(g_i)\")\n6. **Test brackets / asserted-field names** (the field the test asserts on must match the production-path field)\n7. **Recommendation prose** (top-of-doc summary; often the first thing readers see, and the last thing authors update)\n8. **Helper / dataclass docstrings** (return values, field semantics, parameter ordering)\n9. **Pedagogical caveats** (\"note that under v5's convention...\" — version-stamped notes rot)\n10. **Load-bearing constraint callouts** (arm-radius domain, clamp safety floors)\n11. **Derivation paragraphs** (paragraphs that USE parameters to compute bounds: N_LOS, memory, performance gates) — distinct from #1 because they CONSUME parameters\n12. **Narrative-justification paragraphs** (\"X is acceptable because Y\") — distinct from #11 because these don't derive, they only argue\n13. **Compact summary tables** (one-cell restatements of long-form prose — drift HERE persists even after the prose is corrected, because table-row revisions are batched separately from prose revisions and reviewer attention often slides past the table when the prose looks right)\n\nWhen fixing a normative claim, before declaring the fix complete, run `rg` for the corrected token across the whole document. Re-check every match against the surface class. If any class is missing from the grep result but plausibly affected, sweep that surface manually.\n\n### Arithmetic vs justification — audit both separately\n\nClasses #11 (derivation paragraphs) and #12 (narrative-justification paragraphs) are independently auditable. A 14-point arithmetic audit can pass cleanly (every numeric value computes correctly) while justification paragraphs still drift (the REASON given for choosing a number references stale premises). Don't treat them as the same audit.\n\nEmpirically: in observed loops where the arithmetic audit returned clean, ~30% of subsequent rounds still surfaced narrative-justification drift. The right derived bound can be presented with the wrong rationale, and reviewers focused on arithmetic don't catch it. Brief reviewers to audit both classes explicitly.\n\n### Convergence as surface-class exhaustion\n\nThe empirical convergence signal is NOT \"we ran enough rounds.\" It's \"the surface classes we've discovered are now all swept, and one full clean round confirms no NEW class has surfaced.\"\n\nTrack which audit-surface classes have produced findings. When the same classes recur for 2-3 rounds with diminishing-magnitude findings, and one round returns clean from both reviewers without surfacing a new class, the loop has exhausted its attack surface. Convergence is reached when the surface map stops growing AND the existing surfaces all return clean — not when an arbitrary round budget is hit.\n\nIf a new surface class surfaces late in a loop (e.g. \"compact summary tables\" appearing at round 47 after 6 prior rounds of parallel-callout findings), the loop is NOT converged. Add the new class to the audit checklist and run at least one more round.\n\n## Anti-patterns observed in practice\n\n### Heavy-rewrite anti-pattern\n\nA \"heavy rewrite\" — one version bump bundling 4+ substantive fixes — is ~2× more likely to introduce a new bug than five small per-version rewrites. The first verification round after a heavy rewrite should specifically scrutinize the rewrite, not just run the regression checklist.\n\nPrefer small per-version rewrites. If a heavy rewrite is unavoidable (rare), expect at least one fix-the-fix round.\n\n### Fix-the-fix bugs\n\nA precision fix can itself introduce a new precision drift. Example: rewriting \"D&S01 collapsed two scales into one knob\" to \"~3·N_LOS independent corrections\" got the per-LOS framing right but the arithmetic wrong (D&S01 picks ONE component per LOS, so ~N_LOS, not ~3·N_LOS). The fix needs a self-audit against the primary source it cites.\n\nAfter any rewrite that introduces a new factual claim, immediately re-verify the new claim against its primary source before dispatching the next review round. Don't trust your own rewrite.\n\n### Reviewer rationalization\n\nA reviewer (or the user synthesizing findings) can rationalize a contradiction as \"describing the same thing from another angle.\" Example: a summary table that says \"single fit knob, all scales\" can be rationalized as \"describing lack-of-scale-decomposition\" when the literal phrase claims one global knob and contradicts the corrected prose elsewhere.\n\nIf a phrase contains the exact stale framing the fix was supposed to eliminate, the rationalization is wrong. Take the literal reading seriously. If two reviewers disagree on whether a site contradicts itself, treat it as contradicting itself and rewrite.\n\n### Single-reviewer false convergence\n\nConvergence requires BOTH reviewers to clear the round. A single reviewer's \"ship\" is anecdote: in observed 40+ round loops, ~⅓ of rounds have split-decision findings where one reviewer's clean verdict would have shipped a real bug the other caught. If one reviewer is unavailable (tool down, usage limit), either wait or spawn a second-class reviewer (e.g. another general-purpose agent with a hostile-find-orthogonal-items framing) — don't ship on one reviewer.\n\n## Convergence Criteria\n\n**Converged** when ALL of:\n- Both (≥2) reviewers ran this round\n- Neither found new P0 or P1 issues\n- Remaining items are P2 nits, stylistic preferences, or explicitly out-of-scope\n- This round produced zero substantive content changes (or only formatting/wording)\n\n**NOT converged** when ANY of:\n- Only one reviewer ran this round\n- The previous round produced substantive fixes — run at least one more round\n- You stopped because of fatigue, time pressure, or an arbitrary round budget\n- A finding was dismissed without verifying against primary sources\n\nConvergence is empirical. It is not a budget.\n\n## Revision Tracking\n\nBump version on every fix-and-redraft cycle (v9 → v10 → v11). Maintain a revision-history section inside the document:\n\n```markdown\n## Revision history\n\n- **v11 (YYYY-MM-DD):** Fixed Marigo+2017 arXiv ID typo (1701.04915 → 1701.08510, PR review). Set izzard2004 repo_path to null (path didn't exist).\n- **v10 (YYYY-MM-DD):** Reconciled residual framing to cell-coverage metric (was per-star). Corrected slope arithmetic (~47 K → ~135 K).\n- **v9 (YYYY-MM-DD):** Initial draft.\n```\n\nThis:\n- Lets the next round's reviewers see what's been addressed (and not re-flag it)\n- Creates an audit trail when stakeholders ask \"why did this change?\"\n- Forces you to articulate each fix — vague entries reveal vague reasoning\n\n## Keep Supporting Artifacts in Sync\n\nIf the main document references companion files (sources lists, bibliographies, claims/evidence ledgers, sample data, code snippets), **fix all copies in the same commit**. A reviewer that finds a stale reference in one file but not another correctly concludes you don't know which is authoritative — and the next round flags every other file too.\n\nRun a grep for the changed token across the whole repo before committing the fix.\n\n## Common Rationalizations\n\n| Excuse | Reality |\n|--------|---------|\n| \"Codex found nothing this round, we're done\" | One reviewer is one reviewer. Run the second before claiming convergence. |\n| \"I've done 3 rounds, that's enough\" | Convergence is empirical. If round 3 produced substantive fixes, round 4 is required. |\n| \"The fix is obvious, I'll skip verification\" | A meaningful fraction of \"obvious\" fixes apply the wrong patch to the right symptom. 60 seconds of verification beats an hour of rework. |\n| \"Reviewer said X is wrong, so X is wrong\" | Verify against the primary source. Reviewers hallucinate, misread, and reason from stale training data. |\n| \"The supporting files are nits, I'll batch them later\" | Stale references in supporting files invite next-round flags on already-fixed issues. Fix all copies in the same commit. |\n| \"I disagree with the finding, so I'm dropping it\" | Document the disagreement WITH the primary-source citation that supports your position. Silent dismissal looks like sloppiness in the next round. |\n| \"It's already good enough\" | If independent reviewers are still finding load-bearing issues, it isn't. |\n| \"Round-tripping with the reviewer is overkill for this doc\" | If you're tempted to skip, the doc probably wasn't important enough to write down in the first place. Either skip the doc or run the loop. |\n| \"I'll bundle these five fixes into one big rewrite to save a round\" | Heavy rewrites introduce new bugs ~2× more often than small per-version fixes. The \"saved\" round becomes 2-3 fix-the-fix rounds. Land one fix per version. |\n| \"The summary table says X but the prose corrects it — close enough\" | Compact summary tables are a parallel surface. Stale table cells survive prose corrections and become the source an implementer cites. Fix the table in the same commit as the prose. |\n| \"Codex's `gh issue view` returned empty, so the cite is wrong\" | `gh issue view --json body` skips comments. Run `gh issue view N --comments` before declaring a cite false. Reviewer-tool flags matter. |\n\n## Red Flags — Not Converged\n\n- Ran only one reviewer this round\n- Applied a fix without checking the primary source\n- Called convergence after a round that produced substantive changes\n- Reviewer flagged a stale cross-reference you \"already fixed\" — you only fixed one copy\n- Bumped the version but didn't write a revision-history entry\n- Reviewers contradict each other and you picked the one you agreed with without independent verification\n- Only cosmetic changes between the last two rounds (possible Goodhart — verify the underlying claims are still sound)\n- You stopped because you ran out of energy\n\nAny of these means: not converged. Continue the loop.\n\n## What \"Good\" Looks Like\n\nA successfully refined document leaves a trail:\n\n1. ≥2 review rounds, each with ≥2 independent reviewers\n2. A revision history with one entry per cycle, naming the specific fixes\n3. Verified primary-source citations for every load-bearing change\n4. Supporting artifacts (bibliographies, sources lists, code references) consistent across the repo\n5. A final round that produced zero substantive changes\n6. Reviewers' remaining findings are P2 nits or explicit non-goals — documented, not silently dropped\n\nIf you can't point to all six, you're not done yet.\n\n\nARGUMENTS: send few agents to verify most ambiguos parts",
