ult 2s) even when LISTEN/NOTIFY is enabled; when active, NOTIFY merely lets the base poll relax to `notifyPollingIntervalSeconds` (default 30s). Calling this \"LISTEN/NOTIFY for low-latency wake-ups\" as a pg-boss capability without qualifying \"opt-in, polling is the fallback and the default\" is a substantive overstatement. An implementer reading §9.6 who ships without setting `useListenNotify: true` on the instance AND `notify: true` per queue gets 2-second polling, not low-latency delivery.\n\nThe fix is narrow: qualify §9.6 and §23.2 to \"LISTEN/NOTIFY low-latency wake-ups when `useListenNotify` is enabled (polling fallback, 2 s default)\".\n\n---\n\n**P0-2: §21.1 architecture diagram separates pgvector/Qdrant and FTS/Meilisearch as distinct cylinders from PostgreSQL — directly contradicts the Postgres-first premise**\n\nSPEC.md:1833-1835:\n\n```\nRetrieval --&gt; Pg[(PostgreSQL)]\nRetrieval --&gt; Vector[(pgvector / Qdrant)]\nRetrieval --&gt; Lexical[(FTS / Meilisearch)]\n```\n\nThree separate datastore cylinders are drawn: `Pg`, `Vector`, and `Lexical`. In MVP, pgvector and FTS live **inside** the same Postgres node — they are not separate services. The diagram implies three independent stateful backends, contradicting §24.0 (\"one stateful service: PostgreSQL\") and §16.5 (\"PostgreSQL for everything: relational metadata, full-text search (FTS), and embeddings (pgvector)\").\n\nThis is the surface a verification reviewer rationalizes away as \"the diagram shows the logical capability, not deployment topology.\" But the diagram is in an architecture section, uses datastore cylinder notation (the standard symbol for a separate stateful service), and will be read by implementers as a deployment diagram. The diagram needs either (a) a single `Pg[(PostgreSQL + pgvector + FTS)]` cylinder for MVP with a note that Qdrant/Meilisearch are scale-swap alternatives, or (b) an explicit caption distinguishing MVP shape from scale-swap shape. As drawn, it actively misleads anyone mapping it to a `docker-compose.yml`.\n\n---\n\n### P1 Findings\n\n**P1-1: PgBouncer transaction-mode incompatibility with LISTEN/NOTIFY is acknowledged in §24.0 body but the `notifier.ts` source makes it more severe than stated**\n\nSPEC.md:2239 says `LISTEN/NOTIFY` \"needs dedicated connections that don't pool cleanly through PgBouncer in transaction mode.\"\n\nThis is technically accurate, but the notifier.ts source (line 14-16) explicitly lists \"PgBouncer transaction pooling\" as a failure path that causes **silent fallback to polling-only** with only a warning emitted. The spec frames this as an operational caveat (\"Fine at self-host scale\"), but the real consequence is: if the deployment uses PgBouncer in transaction mode (common for connection-constrained environments), LISTEN/NOTIFY silently degrades to polling and the \"low-latency wake-ups\" claim disappears entirely. The spec does not say this. The caveat in §24.0 should state the degradation consequence explicitly, not just note the pooling incompatibility.\n\n---\n\n**P1-2: `pg_trgm` described as \"built-in\" in §24.0 — it is a contrib extension, not a core Postgres built-in**\n\nSPEC.md:2234: \"Required extensions stay minimal: **pgvector** plus the built-in `pg_trgm`\"\n\n`pg_trgm` is a `contrib` module — it requires `CREATE EXTENSION pg_trgm` to activate and is not enabled by default in a stock PostgreSQL installation. Calling it a \"built-in\" is misleading. It ships with the PostgreSQL distribution but is not active without explicit installation. This matters for operators who provision a minimal Postgres image or use a managed PaaS that requires explicit extension enables (e.g., RDS, Supabase). The claim implies zero-configuration; the reality requires one `CREATE EXTENSION` call.\n\nContrast: in the same sentence, `pgvector` is correctly not called a built-in. `pg_trgm` deserves the same framing: \"contrib extension, ships with Postgres but requires `CREATE EXTENSION pg_trgm`.\"\n\n---\n\n**P1-3: §31.2 lists \"Simple scheduled runs\" as a nice-to-have while §9.6/§24.0 put pg-boss scheduling in MVP**\n\nSPEC.md:2851: \"Simple scheduled runs\" under MVP nice-to-have.\nSPEC.md:609: pg-boss provides \"built-in scheduling\" as an MVP queue feature.\nSPEC.md:2226: table row maps \"Scheduled runs\" to \"pg-boss scheduling (or `pg_cron`)\" as the Postgres-first MVP answer.\n\nThe mechanism (pg-boss scheduling infra) is called MVP-included; the user-facing feature (\"simple scheduled runs\") is listed as nice-to-have. This could be defensible if the distinction is architectural plumbing vs exposed UI feature. But it is not stated anywhere that this is the distinction — a reader of §31.2 sees scheduled runs as optional while §9.6 and §24.0 treat scheduling as a first-class MVP component. The inconsistency needs either a note in §31.2 clarifying \"the pg-boss scheduling mechanism is in MVP but the user-facing interface for scheduling is nice-to-have,\" or a demotion of scheduling to nice-to-have in §9.6/§24.0.\n\n---\n\n### P2 Findings\n\n**P2-1: §24.0 table row for \"Full-text search\" conflates tsvector/FTS with pg_trgm**\n\nSPEC.md:2231: `tsvector` + `pg_trgm` (BM25 via `pg_search` if needed)\n\n`tsvector` and `ts_rank` are the FTS mechanism. `pg_trgm` provides trigram-based fuzzy/similarity matching — it is not part of the FTS ranking or retrieval pipeline. Listing them as co-equal parts of the same row implies pg_trgm is a FTS feature when it is a separate search mode (fuzzy match, not lexical rank). P2 because BM25 is correctly attributed to `pg_search`, but the tsvector+pg_trgm conflation is a minor technical inaccuracy that could confuse an implementer about what `pg_trgm` actually provides.\n\n**P2-2: §24.0 claims pg-boss \"needs no Postgres extension\" — technically true today but historically pg_boss required pgcrypto**\n\nSPEC.md:2234 confirms \"pg-boss needs no extension.\" Primary-source verification: pg-boss README (`https://github.com/timgit/pg-boss`, Requirements section) lists only \"PostgreSQL 13 or higher\" — no extension requirement. No mention of `pgcrypto` or `CREATE EXTENSION` in README or source. This claim is **correct** as of the current version. No finding here beyond confirming correctness.\n\n**P2-3: §27.1 Docker Compose profiles describe the `postgres` service as \"also runs the queue, scheduler, cache, FTS, vectors (§24.0)\" — accurate, but the scale-swap profiles list `cache-redis` without removing the queue comment**\n\nSPEC.md:2516: `postgres # pgvector image; also runs the queue, scheduler, cache, FTS, vectors`\nSPEC.md:2524: `cache-redis # scale swap: high-QPS cache / queue (§23.4, §24.0)`\n\nThe `cache-redis` comment says \"cache / queue\" as if activating the Redis profile also swaps the queue. Per §23.4, the queue swap (pg-boss → Redis+BullMQ) is a separate decision from the cache swap. The comment implies both happen together. Minor, but implementers reading profiles will interpret \"cache-redis\" as swapping both. Should read \"cache\" only, or clarify that queue swap requires separate configuration.\n\n---\n\n## Verdict\n\n**NOT CONVERGED.**\n\nThree load-bearing issues remain: the LISTEN/NOTIFY overstatement (P0-1) will mislead implementers about default pg-boss behavior and latency guarantees; the architecture diagram (P0-2) contradicts the Postgres-first premise by drawing pgvector and FTS as separate services; and the pg_trgm \"built-in\" claim (P1-2) is factually incorrect.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>69951</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>21</tool_uses><duration_ms>322895</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>",
